# Move an Apideck File Storage File Into a New Folder

## Background
Apideck Unified File Storage exposes the OneDrive connector that has been pre-configured on this consumer. The unified API lets you create folders, upload files, and move existing files into different parent folders, all behind the single base URL `https://unify.apideck.com` (uploads use `https://upload.apideck.com`).

You will run a one-off script that, against the configured OneDrive drive, creates a fresh destination folder, uploads a small text file at the drive root, and then moves that file into the new folder using a single PATCH call. The final filesystem state in OneDrive will be checked through the unified API.

## Requirements
- Read every Apideck credential and target from environment variables: `APIDECK_APP_ID`, `APIDECK_API_KEY`, `APIDECK_CONSUMER_ID`, `APIDECK_FILE_STORAGE_DRIVE_NAME`, and `ZEALT_RUN_ID`.
- Use the OneDrive connector (`x-apideck-service-id: onedrive`) for every File Storage request.
- Resolve the target drive by name (matching `APIDECK_FILE_STORAGE_DRIVE_NAME`) via the List Drives endpoint before any other action.
- Create a brand-new destination folder under the drive root whose name embeds the current `run-id` so concurrent runs do not collide.
- Upload a small text file at the drive root whose name embeds the current `run-id`.
- After the upload succeeds, issue a PATCH call against the file resource that reparents it under the newly created folder (rather than re-uploading it).
- Append a line to the log file describing the resulting state with the file ID and the destination folder ID returned by Apideck.

## Implementation Hints
- The Unified File Storage REST surface lives at `https://unify.apideck.com`, but direct binary uploads (`POST /file-storage/files`) must be sent to `https://upload.apideck.com`. The file body is raw binary; the per-upload metadata (`name`, `parent_folder_id`, optional `drive_id`) must be JSON-encoded into the `x-apideck-metadata` request header.
- Every File Storage request must include three Apideck headers (`Authorization: Bearer ...`, `x-apideck-app-id`, `x-apideck-consumer-id`) plus `x-apideck-service-id: onedrive` because more than one connector could be enabled for the consumer.
- `GET /file-storage/drives` returns each drive's `id` and `name`. Use it to find the drive whose `name` equals `APIDECK_FILE_STORAGE_DRIVE_NAME`, then pass that drive's `id` as `drive_id` when creating the folder and (optionally) when uploading the file.
- `POST /file-storage/folders` accepts `name`, `parent_folder_id` (use `"root"` for the drive root), and `drive_id`. The response body's `data.id` is the new folder's unified ID.
- For the move, use `PATCH /file-storage/files/{id}` with body `{"parent_folder_id": "<new_folder_id>"}`. Do **not** re-upload the file; the same `id` returned by the upload must be reparented in place.
- The Python `apideck-unify` SDK or plain `httpx`/`requests` calls both work. If you use the SDK, make sure it is configured with the OneDrive `service_id`.
- The OneDrive connector does not support creating drives, share links, downloads, or exports through the unified API. Only call List Drives, Create Folder, Upload File, and PATCH File for this task.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Project path: /home/user/myproject
- Ensure the script is executed end-to-end and the real Apideck/OneDrive side effects are applied before verification.
- Log file: /home/user/myproject/output.log
- The destination folder must be created at the drive root of the drive whose name equals `APIDECK_FILE_STORAGE_DRIVE_NAME` and its name must be `apideck-move-folder-${ZEALT_RUN_ID}`.
- The moved file must have the name `apideck-move-file-${ZEALT_RUN_ID}.txt` and its `parent_folders` (as returned by `GET /file-storage/files`) must contain the destination folder created above.
- The log file `/home/user/myproject/output.log` must contain a line in the format `File moved: file_id=<file_id> folder_id=<folder_id>` where `<file_id>` is the Apideck unified file ID returned by the upload (and surfaced again by the PATCH/GET) and `<folder_id>` is the unified ID returned by Create Folder.


