# Assign an Apideck Issue Tracking Ticket to a Collection User (Python SDK)

## Background
[Apideck](https://www.apideck.com/) Unified Issue Tracking exposes a single ticket model that maps to providers such as Jira, Linear, and GitHub. To assign work to a teammate, you cannot pass a raw username — the `assignees` array on the unified ticket model expects an array of objects keyed by Apideck-resolved user `id`. Those ids must first be looked up via [`GET /issue-tracking/collections/{collection_id}/users`](https://developers.apideck.com/md/apis/issue-tracking/reference/users.md). In this task you will use the official [`apideck-unify` Python SDK](https://developers.apideck.com/sdks/python.md) to (1) list the users in the preconfigured GitHub-backed collection, (2) deterministically pick one of them, and (3) create a new ticket that is assigned to that user. The result must be re-verifiable through the unified API.

## Requirements
- Use the official `apideck-unify` Python SDK for every Apideck call (do **not** call REST endpoints with `requests`/`curl`, and do **not** use the Node `@apideck/unify` SDK).
- Read `APIDECK_APP_ID`, `APIDECK_API_KEY`, `APIDECK_CONSUMER_ID`, `APIDECK_ISSUE_TRACKING_COLLECTION_ID`, and `ZEALT_RUN_ID` from the environment. The Issue Tracking service id is `github`.
- Resolve a candidate user by listing the users on the configured collection and **picking the user whose `id` sorts first lexicographically** (use Python's natural string ordering). If the collection has no users, the task fails — do **not** fall back to a hard-coded id.
- Create exactly one ticket on the configured collection (`APIDECK_ISSUE_TRACKING_COLLECTION_ID`) with:
  - `subject` exactly `Assign demo - ${ZEALT_RUN_ID}`.
  - `description` exactly `Assignment created by assign_ticket_to_user_py for run ${ZEALT_RUN_ID}`.
  - `assignees` containing a single entry whose `id` is the user id you resolved above. Do not include other optional fields (the GitHub connector does not support `priority` and similar fields).
- Persist a single-line JSON artifact at `/home/user/myproject/assignment.json` with the following exact shape:

  ```json
  {
    "run_id": "<ZEALT_RUN_ID>",
    "collection_id": "<APIDECK_ISSUE_TRACKING_COLLECTION_ID>",
    "user_id": "<resolved user id>",
    "ticket_id": "<created ticket id>",
    "ticket_subject": "Assign demo - <ZEALT_RUN_ID>"
  }
  ```

  All values must be strings. The file content must parse with `json.loads` and the top level must be an object with exactly these five keys.

## Implementation Hints
- Install the SDK with `pip install apideck-unify` and instantiate it with the credentials read from the environment.
- The user list call typically looks like `apideck.issue_tracking.users.list(service_id="github", collection_id=...)`. The list response exposes the entries on `get_users_response.data` (or the SDK's documented attribute) — iterate them and pick the entry whose `id` is the smallest string.
- The ticket create call expects the unified ticket fields and `service_id="github"`; pass `assignees=[{"id": user_id}]`.
- Suggested references: [Issue Tracking reference](https://developers.apideck.com/apis/issue-tracking/reference), [List Users](https://developers.apideck.com/md/apis/issue-tracking/reference/users.md), [Create Ticket](https://developers.apideck.com/md/apis/issue-tracking/reference/tickets/collectionTicketsAdd.md), [Get Ticket](https://developers.apideck.com/md/apis/issue-tracking/reference/tickets/collectionTicketsOne.md), [Python SDK guide](https://developers.apideck.com/sdks/python.md).

## Acceptance Criteria
- Project path: /home/user/myproject
- Ensure the seeding and assignment are executed against the real Apideck Issue Tracking API and the artifact exists.
- Log/artifact file: /home/user/myproject/assignment.json (JSON only; the file must be valid JSON and must parse with `json.loads`).
- The JSON object must have exactly the five top-level keys `run_id`, `collection_id`, `user_id`, `ticket_id`, and `ticket_subject`, and every value must be a non-empty string.
  - `run_id` must equal the current `ZEALT_RUN_ID`.
  - `collection_id` must equal the current `APIDECK_ISSUE_TRACKING_COLLECTION_ID`.
  - `ticket_subject` must equal `Assign demo - ${ZEALT_RUN_ID}`.
- The `user_id` value must appear in the live List Users response for the configured collection (i.e., it must be a real user known to the Apideck Issue Tracking API for that collection) and must be the lexicographically smallest user id in that list.
- The `ticket_id` value must be retrievable via Get Ticket on the same collection, with the server-side subject matching `ticket_subject` and with at least one entry in `data.assignees` whose `id` equals `user_id`.
- Any persisted solution file under `/home/user/myproject` that performs Apideck calls must use the `apideck-unify` Python SDK (e.g., `import apideck_unify` or `from apideck_unify import Apideck`); no persisted file may shell out to `curl` or call `requests`/`httpx` against `*.apideck.com` for the listing, creation, or any other Apideck operation.


